&gt; Hi Grant, welcome to the group.
&gt; 
&gt; Issue #1: Shouldn&#39;t the base dialect be more neutral?
&gt; 
&gt; Just because there is a base dialect does not mean that you have to 
&gt; speak that way. It does mean that you have to be familiar with the 
&gt; dialect if that is the basis of standardized spelling.
&gt; 
&gt; Currently English spelling is based on a dialect that no one speaks, 
&gt; some have argued that it is more or less based on Elizabethan 
&gt; English. 
&gt; 
&gt; It will be much easier for all to phonemically spell as an NBC 
&gt; commentator speaks than as Queen Elizabeth spoke. I don&#39;t think the 
&gt; issue is proper pronunciation. It is more a case of a pronunciation 
&gt; that will be widely understood.
&gt; 
&gt; For non published material people can write other dialects.
&gt; 
&gt; Issue #2 I just heard that Read had improved his
&gt; original and so I just skipped straight to Quikscript. But from
&gt; discussions here it would seem that the Shavian community is
&gt; considerably bigger. Does anyone know why? Is it just that it&#39;s 
&gt; older? 
&gt; 
&gt; Unlike Shavian, Quickscript received virtually no press. It also 
&gt; represents an abandonment of the analytical approach found in the 
&gt; Shaw alphabet. Quickscript corrects one typo in Shavian and 
&gt; simplifies the orthography. It is an improvement on many dimensions 
&gt; but not all. 
&gt; 
&gt; Regards,
&gt; 
